06:14.300 --> 06:19.460
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

06:22.540 --> 06:23.800
And here are your hosts.

06:28.480 --> 06:29.460
This is Daryl Lane.

06:29.780 --> 06:30.420
And Bill Vernon.

06:31.020 --> 06:34.660
Fred Saber Hagen has been a professional science fiction author for some 17 years.

06:35.200 --> 06:36.880
His output is notable for its variety.

06:36.880 --> 06:42.360
Even though he writes typical science fiction, good science fiction such as the popular Berserkers

06:42.360 --> 06:44.620
series, he tries related areas too.

06:45.700 --> 06:49.580
Well, I like to change back and forth.

06:49.840 --> 06:57.860
I think I get a little tired of doing whatever it is I'm doing after a long book, and then

06:57.860 --> 07:02.500
I like to do something as different as I can find from that.

07:03.360 --> 07:07.720
One of his novels that varies from straight science fiction is The Huge Empire of the East,

07:08.040 --> 07:10.240
a story with the characteristics of science fantasy.

07:11.200 --> 07:16.240
Originally there were three books, The Broken Lands, Black Mountains, and Changeling Earth.

07:17.300 --> 07:26.080
And they came out some years earlier with split up among two different publishers as it happened,

07:26.240 --> 07:30.280
the way problems of publishing and everything being of what they are.

07:31.360 --> 07:35.360
Magic works in The Empire of the East and sorcery is an occupation.

07:36.040 --> 07:41.020
And this is so because the structure of atoms has been changed, making nuclear power and technology impossible.

07:41.540 --> 07:45.180
But at the novel's end there's a tremendous battle between inhuman forces.

07:45.720 --> 07:49.620
One is Orcus, a demon power that represents the irrational into magic.

07:50.780 --> 07:56.280
The other is Ardna, a super machine which has gathered enough strength to challenge the magical foundation of the world.

07:56.640 --> 07:58.400
The result of the battle is a balance.

07:58.400 --> 08:00.980
Technology and magic will coexist.

08:02.180 --> 08:09.120
The world was changing again and at least for a time both of these kinds of powers would be functional.

08:10.300 --> 08:14.140
In 1976, Saber Hagen published a horror story in the classic tradition,

08:14.820 --> 08:19.980
a mysterious house, an unknown force haunting it, a family buying the house and moving in.

08:20.680 --> 08:21.600
The book is Specimens.

08:22.700 --> 08:28.460
Kind of a fun story if you can call it that, of a menace to be overcome.

08:29.020 --> 08:36.460
The old house in the story by the way really exists in Lombard, or dead a few years ago.

08:37.240 --> 08:44.560
When we lived in Chicago we were looking for houses in the area there and that was one that we looked at.

08:45.660 --> 08:48.740
The power haunting the house is an alien living beneath it.

08:48.740 --> 08:53.820
It's been there for centuries, even before the house was built, capturing humans as specimens.

08:54.800 --> 09:02.200
It was an attempt to write a good Grade B movie plot and nobody has bought it yet to make a good Grade B movie,

09:02.540 --> 09:08.020
but there's a new Ace Edition coming out in a few months here and maybe somebody will.

09:09.080 --> 09:15.360
Another facet of Saber Hagen's variety is seen in a little known satire, Love Conquers All, which came out in 1974.

09:15.360 --> 09:23.520
It extrapolates strongly from present social trends and in that sense is reminiscent of Paul and Cornbluth's advertising classic, The Space Merchants.

09:23.680 --> 09:27.240
But Saber Hagen extrapolates from something very different than advertising.

09:28.200 --> 09:42.500
I guess it was the controversy about abortion and sex and things were bombarded, questions were faced with all the time here.

09:44.380 --> 09:58.220
And I just tried to, you know, one of the traditional science fiction writers' viewpoint, take a look at everything, turn everything inside out and see how it looks from the other point of view.

09:59.140 --> 10:04.040
In Love Conquers All, Saber Hagen totally reverses all our present attitudes towards sex and love.

10:04.680 --> 10:09.560
The book presents a world in which a wife should have affairs, in which virginity is horrifying.

10:09.560 --> 10:14.940
And as a clever touch, the curses people use are words like purity and chastity.

10:15.980 --> 10:21.000
We asked Saber Hagen if the book had a message. Was it satire? Was he on a soapbox?

10:22.420 --> 10:33.700
No, I think that's your department really. Whether it's satire or what it is, I think I've done my job when I've written it.

10:34.440 --> 10:40.160
So I wouldn't say you're wrong. Classify it however you will.

10:41.000 --> 10:43.180
Tomorrow, more of Fred Saber Hagen.

11:43.560 --> 11:47.480
Coming up next is the science fiction radio show, so stay with us.

12:02.860 --> 12:08.180
This is the science fiction radio show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

12:10.820 --> 12:12.500
And here are your hosts.

12:17.480 --> 12:19.340
This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lange.

12:19.760 --> 12:25.240
Dracula, the fearsome vampire of legend and myth. You wouldn't think anything new could be written on him.

12:25.740 --> 12:30.700
But science fiction author Fred Saber Hagen thought otherwise. So far he's written five novels on Dracula.

12:31.980 --> 12:38.720
The Dracula tape is the first one, which is a recounting of the original Ram Stoker's original Dracula story.

12:39.200 --> 12:49.520
Only seen from the point of view of the count. And there's Holmes Dracula and an old friend of the family and Thorne, which is out now.

12:51.260 --> 12:58.320
Since we spoke with Saber Hagen, the fifth book in the series, Dominion, has come out. We ask him how he got interested in Dracula.

12:59.440 --> 13:10.820
Well, it started, I just sat down one day and just for fun. I wanted to reread the original Dracula, which I had read once before, years earlier.

13:12.220 --> 13:20.820
And I think it's not all that good a book really, apart from this titanic devilish central character.

13:20.820 --> 13:28.100
But it struck me more and more as I read through it that Dracula was hardly ever on stage.

13:29.660 --> 13:36.460
And this thing, everybody's talking about him and he's almost always off somewhere doing something. Nobody quite knows what.

13:39.480 --> 13:44.120
So I guess maybe I had Rosencrantz and Guildenstern are dead on my mind or something like that.

13:44.120 --> 13:50.100
But I just thought, what would it look like from the chief villains point of view?

13:51.340 --> 13:57.360
So off I went. It was awful lot of fun to write and it just seemed to go right along.

13:58.460 --> 14:01.880
The first book was the Dracula tape published in 1975.

14:02.680 --> 14:10.540
In this novel, Dracula is telling what really happened to Lucy, Professor Van Helsing and Jonathan, the characters from the Brahms Stoker novel.

14:10.540 --> 14:15.740
As it turns out, the count is a victim of circumstances and Van Helsing is a demented loony.

14:16.300 --> 14:21.160
In Saberhagen's account, the vampire almost never kills anyone. He just takes a court to go.

14:21.820 --> 14:28.180
It was Van Helsing who was accidentally killing the victims by giving them blood transfusions from persons whose blood type didn't match.

14:28.820 --> 14:33.240
And readers liked it. It was something different, Dracula from the vampire's point of view.

14:33.780 --> 14:39.560
And Saberhagen had something different, even unique, for the sequel, entitled The Holmes Dracula File.

14:40.600 --> 14:43.720
The time came to think about doing a sequel for it.

14:43.940 --> 14:51.660
And it occurred to me that nobody had ever put Holmes and Dracula in the same book up to that point as far as I knew.

14:53.240 --> 14:57.740
And it seemed to me they, this would be very interesting.

14:57.980 --> 15:05.420
It's as if they represented the two sides of the human psyche or the intellect and the dark side.

15:05.420 --> 15:12.300
And here they were, they were contemporaries. They were in the same city, in the same year.

15:12.900 --> 15:22.340
And everybody knew about them both and still they'd never, they just completely missed each other.

15:22.440 --> 15:25.400
So I decided I had to try to make contact there someplace.

15:27.160 --> 15:35.000
Can Saberhagen's Dracula material be considered science fiction? Its popularity is obvious, but does it attract science fiction readers or some other type?

15:35.740 --> 15:40.720
Sometimes you see it on the fantasy shelf in the bookstore. Sometimes you see it in occult.

15:42.620 --> 15:54.280
Sometimes you see it on the new shelf or only the zombies and haunted babies and all these modern recent things appear.

15:55.440 --> 15:58.660
I don't really care as long as people are reading it.

15:59.100 --> 16:02.120
I don't know if they're science fiction readers. Some of them think they're vampires.

16:03.440 --> 16:07.080
You get a pretty good, maybe some of them are vampires.

16:07.720 --> 16:12.140
How do the Dracula books compare with Saberhagen's other books in terms of reader response?

16:13.360 --> 16:19.000
I think what's got the biggest reader response by far is the Dracula books I've done.

16:20.240 --> 16:27.020
I get more, more letters and mail and sometimes more money.

